abstract: CINCINNATI, July 4. -- Now-York's Giants celebrated the Fourth in great style hers to-day. They won two games from the Reds, and as Chicago was whipped twice by Brooklyn, are once more in the lead. Both games were well attended and at times excitement ran high. "Buck" Ewing was advertised to catch, but he didn't. He contented himself by greeting his Cincinnati townsmen.

abstract: CHARLESTON, S.C., July 4. -- At the annual meeting of the Laurens County Alliance at Laurens, S.C., yesterday they had a lively time and the meeting came near ending in bloodshed and riot. The occurrence is made one of especial interest by the fact that United States Senator J.L.M. Irby was one of the principals in the difficulty.

abstract: CHICAGO, July 4. -- Ward's men administered two signal defeats to Anson's championship aspirants. They made the Chicagos step from the front rank in the League race and allowed the New-Yorks to take the coveted position. In the morning game Chicago was badly beaten, but the afternoon contest proved to be a struggle of the hottest kind. Eleven innings were played, but the Bridegrooms came out on top the 1 run necessary to win.

abstract: MONTREAL, June 29. -- When the Allan Line steamship Montevidean arrived in port early this morning the officers gave an account of thrilling voyage. The Montevidean left London for this port on June 13 with 2,000 tons of general cargo. The passage was an uneventful one until the steamer got a little eastward of Cape Ray on Wednesday last. At 2 o'clock in the afternoon a dense smoke was noticed coming from No. 5 afterhold.

abstract: HARLESTON, S.C., July 4. -- Cheraw, one of the oldest and most historic towns in South Carolina, has the honor of being the first in the State to return to an ancient custom of celebrating Independence Day with a big demonstration. The people from the surrounding country turned out en masse to take part in the celebration, and were joined in honoring the day by large delegations from North Carolina.

abstract: PEEKSKILL, N.Y., July 5. -- Life in the Camp of Instruction to-day has been an unmixed joy for the New-Yorkers and their rural comrades in arms, for there has been a minimum of instruction and an overwhelming preponderance of pleasure. abstract: The most vivid account of the remarkable escape of twenty passengers from death last Thursday night near Rosebud is given by E. Benninghoven of Chicago, who was in the Pullman that plunged into the Yellowstone. He boarded the train at St. Paul for Helena. Kline of Cuyahoga County.

abstract: Fire was discovered shortly after midnight las night in the cellars of the four-story brick tenements 268 and 270 State Street, Brooklyn. The houses were each occupied by eight families, all of whom had a narrow escape, so quick was the onslaught of the flames. From the cellar of 268 the fire made its way up the dumb-waiter shaft through the halls to the roof. The buildings were completely gutted.

abstract: JOSHUA, Johnson County, Texas, July 14. -- This morning at 1 o'clock two men went to the home of George Newberry, living two miles west of Joshua, and demanded admittance. Mr. Newberry being absent, his mother supposed that it was he returning, and opened the door. The men forced their way into the house and demanded money that they supposed had been received by Mr. Newberry a few days previously.

abstract: An incendiary fire yesterday morning destroyed the block extending from the Central Hotel to the electric light station in Altoona, Penn. The guests of the Leonard House escaped with their effects, but the building was gutted. The loss will be about $2,500, with no insurance. Other losses are: Besant  Henneman, wholesale grocers, $15,000, insurance 7,000; George F. Street, hides and leather, $13,000, insurance $5,100; James C. Watts  Co., commission merchants, 5,000, insurance $2,000.

Davis of the American Medical Temperance Association of Chicago, Ill., who presided Wednesday, was again in the chair.

abstract: Prof. F.W. TAUSSIG presents in the Quarterly Journal of Economics a clear and interesting discussion of the theory which determines the rates charged for transportation by railway companies. Doubtless the practice has grown out of the exigencies of traffic without much reference to scientific theories, but the principles which have determined it, whether consciously or unconsciously to the managers, may nevertheless be deduced with some approach to accuracy.

abstract: DOGS ON MONEY. -- There is an important group of about forty coins containing outlines of dogs, which deserve careful study. The interest of some of them is mainly mythical, as with Laelaps, the hound of Actaeon, presented to Cephalos by Procris; or with the dog of Segeste, which symbolized the river Crimisus. But there are enough to show how extensive were the operations of the dog fancier in early times.

abstract: The Farmers' Alliance in Maryland seems to be working very much as it worked in South Carolina before the election of TILLMAN. It is not working as a third party or for an independent ticket, but is seeking to control the action of the Democratic Party. It has a favored candidate for Governor, but he is a Democrat, and the Alliance intends to secure his nomination by the Democratic Convention.

abstract: The seizure by the Dominion cruiser Dream of several American fishing boats belonging to Eastport is a reminder of the almost total eclipse thus far during the present season of what used to be a fiery and menacing dispute in that region.
